All four areas of your app hit .NET 11 behavioral breaking changes. Here's what breaks and how to fix each:

---

### 1. GZipStream empty payload now writes headers/footers
In .NET 10, compressing zero bytes produced 0-length output. In .NET 11, valid GZip headers/footers are always written, so `ms.Length > 0` even with no data.

**Fix:** Don't check output stream length for zero. Instead, track whether you actually wrote any data:
```csharp
// Before (.NET 10): if (ms.Length == 0) { /* no data */ }
// After (.NET 11): track it yourself
bool wroteData = false;
using (var gz = new GZipStream(ms, CompressionMode.Compress, leaveOpen: true))
{
    if (hasData) { gz.Write(buffer); wroteData = true; }
}
if (!wroteData) { /* no data scenario */ }
```

---

### 2. TAR header checksum validation is now enforced
`TarReader` now verifies header checksums. Your hand-crafted legacy TAR files with invalid checksums will **throw** on `GetNextEntry()`.

**Fix:** Add error handling, or fix the legacy tool to produce valid checksums:
```csharp
try
{
    var entry = reader.GetNextEntry();
}
catch (InvalidDataException ex) when (ex.Message.Contains("checksum"))
{
    // Handle legacy TAR files with bad checksums
}
```

---

### 3. ZipArchive.CreateAsync now eagerly loads entries
Entries are no longer lazy-loaded — they're all read into memory immediately. For your large ZIP files this may cause **increased memory pressure**.

**Fix:** Monitor memory usage. Consider processing entries in streaming fashion or breaking up very large archives if memory becomes an issue.

---

### 4. MemoryStream maximum capacity changed
The maximum capacity and exception behavior for `MemoryStream` have been updated. Your very large allocations near the old maximum may hit different limits or throw different exception types.

**Fix:** Review code that catches specific exception types (e.g., `OutOfMemoryException`) around large `MemoryStream` allocations. Test with your actual allocation sizes on .NET 11 to confirm behavior.

---

**Summary:** Items 1–3 are the most likely to cause visible failures. Item 1 is a silent logic bug (your "no data" detection stops working). Item 2 will throw at runtime. Item 3 could cause OOM for large archives. Item 4 needs testing with your specific allocation sizes.
